                <para>
                    Result of adding this correction to the mean lunar anomaly is called 'corrected lunar anomaly'.
                </para>
                <para role="notes">
                    Rambam does not describe the model behind this correction. 
                    Because the models Rambam did describe until now are the same as Ptolemy's models
                    (including numerical parameters), and because this correction is determined by the (doubled)
                    sun-moon elongation, just like Ptolemy's "improved" model of the moon ("the crank"),
                    I assume that that model was used to calculate this correction. We'll see how does the curve fit.
                </para>
                <para role="notes">
                    TODO: Derive the formula! Make the diagram! Make another diagram - for the "simple" model!
                    {How come the fact that sun and moon move in different plains does not affect this calculation?}
                </para>
                <para role="notes">
                    It seems that Rambam treats "the crank" as just a calculation device - otherwise,
                    table giving visible anomaly from the corrected anomaly should take into account changes in the
                    earth-moon distance depending on the elongation - and it does not!
                    Maybe that is why he does not describe the model behind this correction.
                    And maybe this is why Rambam reiterates - in Law 2 - that only the observability of the new moon
                    needs to be calculated correctly. {How did Ptolemy calculate visible anomaly?}
                </para>
            </section>
            <section>
                <title>Law 4</title>
                <para>
                    Afterwards, see how many degrees is corrected lunar anomaly.
                    If it is less than 180°, subtract mnas of this corrected anomaly from the mean moon at the
                    observation time. An if corrected lunar anomaly is is more than 180° but less than 360°,
                    add mnas of this corrected anomaly to the mean moon at the observation time.
                    And mean moon after you add to it or subtract from it is the true location of the Moon at
                    the observation time.
                </para>
            </section>
            <section>
                <title>Law 5</title>
                <para>
                    You should know that if the corrected anomaly is 180° or 360°, it does not have a mona,
                    so mean moon at the observation time is also true location.
                </para>
            </section>

